From: mbt28 <btekbas@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 2/6] media: cedrus: h264: reset macroblock position registers
 on new frames

The BSP decoder (libawh264 H264ConfigureSliceRegister) writes 0 to the
current-macroblock counter (0x22c) and the macroblock x/y register
(0x260) whenever it sets up the first slice of a picture.  cedrus never
touches either register and relies on the engine reloading the position
from the slice header registers, leaving whatever state the previous
picture ended with in place.

Match the BSP and clear both registers when a new frame starts.  This
is cheap, faithful to the only known-good programming sequence for the
first-generation engines, and harmless on later revisions.

Signed-off-by: mbt28 <btekbas@gmail.com>
---
 drivers/staging/media/sunxi/cedrus/cedrus_h264.c | 12 ++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+)

--- a/drivers/staging/media/sunxi/cedrus/cedrus_h264.c
+++ b/drivers/staging/media/sunxi/cedrus/cedrus_h264.c
@@ -391,6 +391,18 @@
 	}
 
 	/*
+	 * The BSP H.264 decoder clears the macroblock position
+	 * registers when it configures the first slice of a picture
+	 * (libawh264 H264ConfigureSliceRegister); the hardware
+	 * otherwise starts from whatever position the previous
+	 * picture left behind.
+	 */
+	if (ctx->fh.m2m_ctx->new_frame) {
+		cedrus_write(dev, VE_H264_CUR_MB_NUM, 0);
+		cedrus_write(dev, VE_H264_MB_ADDR, 0);
+	}
+
+	/*
 	 * FIXME: Since the bitstream parsing is done in software, and
 	 * in userspace, this shouldn't be needed anymore. But it
 	 * turns out that removing it breaks the decoding process,
